thread.title: 5-0 Record for Temple Is Its First Since 1974
thread.title_full: 5-0 Record for Temple Is Its First Since 1974 - The New York Times

author: The Associated Press
title: 5-0 Record for Temple Is Its First Since 1974
text:
Jahad Thomas and Ryquell Armstead each scored two touchdowns, and host Temple remained unbeaten with a 49-10 victory over Tulane on Saturday.
The Owls (5-0, 2-0 American Athletic Conference), who have opened with five wins for the first time since 1974, ended a two-game winning streak by the Green Wave (2-3, 1-1).
Thomas ran 10 yards to give Temple a 14-10 lead in the second quarter and added 16-yard scoring catch from P. J. Walker for a 21-10 halftime lead.
Armstead, making his first start, added two 16-yard touchdown runs in the third quarter, sandwiched around Sean Chandler’s 22-yard interception return for a score.
PENN STATE 29, INDIANA 7 Christian Hackenberg threw for 262 yards and two touchdowns and ran for two scores, and Penn State (5-1, 2-0 Big Ten) beat visiting Indiana (4-2, 0-2).
Hackenberg, who was 21 of 39, hit Brandon Polk and DaeSean Hamilton on 39-yard scoring strikes in the first half. He cut upfield for the longest run of his career — a 22-yard dash that powered a second-quarter drive — and turned a bootleg into a 1-yard touchdown run for a 19-7 halftime lead two plays later.
PITTSBURGH 26, VIRGINIA 19 Pittsburgh forced Virginia quarterback Matt Johns into four straight incompletions in the final minute to preserve a win at home.
Nate Peterman passed for 222 yards and two touchdowns for Pitt (4-1, 2-0 Atlantic Coast Conference), and Chris James ran for 94 yards. Qadree Ollison rushed for 49 yards and a score but also fumbled at the Virginia 1 in the fourth quarter, allowing the Cavaliers (1-4, 0-1) to keep the game close.
DUKE 44, ARMY 3 Thomas Sirk threw for 197 yards and a touchdown, Jela Duncan and Parker Boehme each scored twice, and the Duke defense did the rest in a victory over mistake-prone Army.
It was the worst loss for Army (1-5) at Michie Stadium since Baylor beat the Black Knights by 55-0 in 1979.
The win for Duke (5-1) improved its record to 11-1 in its last 12 road games, and the Blue Devils are 5-1 in consecutive years for the first time since 1952-53.
FORDHAM 48, PENN 45 Chase Edmonds rushed for 230 yards and scored four touchdowns for Fordham, but it was a 31-yard field goal by Makay Redd with eight seconds left that gave the Rams (5-1) a win at Pennsylvania (1-3).
Andrew Lisa’s third touchdown pass, a 13-yarder to Ryan Kelly, and 2-point conversion to Justin Watson pulled Penn, which had trailed by 25 late in the second quarter, into a tie with 1 minute 46 seconds to play. But Kevin Anderson, who completed 29 of 36 passes for a career-high 377 yards and two touchdowns, took the Rams 51 yards in nine plays to pull out the win.
HARVARD 40, CORNELL 3 Scott Hosch threw three touchdown passes and ran for another score, and visiting Harvard beat Cornell to win its 18th straight game.
The Crimson (4-0, 2-0 Ivy League) outgained Cornell (0-4, 0-2) by 499 total yards to 192 and converted one of three interceptions and a fumble into scores.
DARTMOUTH 35, YALE 3 Dalyn Williams passed for a career-high 435 yards and four touchdowns to help host Dartmouth (4-0, 2-0 Ivy) beat Yale (3-1, 1-1).
Williams became Dartmouth’s career leader in total offense (7,525), passing the former N.F.L. quarterback Jay Fiedler (1991-93). Williams moved past Brian Mann into second on the team’s career passing list with 6,080 yards, trailing only Fiedler (6,684).
PRINCETON 44, COLGATE 20 John Lovett had four rushing touchdowns, and Princeton (4-0) beat visiting Colgate (2-4).
Lovett gained 49 yards on 14 carries. Chad Kanoff was 25 of 41 for 277 yards, and Isaiah Barnes had eight catches for 92 yards.
BROWN 25, HOLY CROSS 24 Grant Senne kicked a 35-yard field goal with 2:06 left to help Brown (2-2) win at Holy Cross (2-3).
Senne’s kick capped an 11-play, 63-yard drive — the big play coming on a 14-yard completion from Marcus Fuller to Alexander Jette on third-and-6 to the Holy Cross 24.
